March 12, 2012 12:00 p.m.      Updated 3/12/2012 

Jose Maria Alapont to retire as Federal-Mogul CEO; Rainer Jueckstock to replace himBy Dustin Walsh 

TwitterFacebookLinkedInGoogle+CommentsEmailPrinter-friendly version 


Automotive


Federal-Mogul Corp.










Jose Maria Alapont
 


Federal-Mogul Corp. CEO Jose Maria Alapont will retire at the end of the month, the company said today.
Alapont, 61, will be replaced by Rainer Jueckstock, current senior vice president of the Southfield-based supplier's powertrain energy business unit. Jueckstock also will join the company's board of directors April 1.
Alapont, who became CEO in 2005, will remain with Federal-Mogul in a consulting role and remain on the board through 2013, according to a release.
Before joining Federal-Mogul, Alapont was CEO and a board member of Turin, Italy-based Iveco, the commercial-vehicle manufacturing arm of the Fiat Group. He also served in various positions, many of them executive titles, at Delphi Corp., the French supplier Valeo SA and Ford Motor Co. 
Federal-Mogul also announced that it is creating an independent aftermarket powertrain and safety division. Its aftermarket division as a whole generated $2.3 billion in revenue last year.
After the announcement, shares of Federal-Mogul (Nasdaq: FDML) were up nearly 3 percent in morning trading to $17.49.















 




 









 






